<br>
His big thing was to make sure those kids got out of that class knowing exactly where every country on the planet was, and he would give them that test over and over.  It's sad that this had to be done to these kids in college, instead of, I dunno, in 4th grade. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nakath>Nakath</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 421<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/1/03 2:25:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=386.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What the hell?!?!?</span><hr size=1> Its not the fault of the 'education system' its the result of the ridiculous political games that are played with that system.<br>
<br>
People ask 'what has happened to our schools?'<br>
<br>
You wanna know what happened? Local governments had control taken away from them.<br>
<br>
The USA that landed a man on the moon, defeated polio and smallpox, developed atomic fission, invented the computer and the personal computer and created the richest nation in the history of mankind was educated in a system that was almost 100% locally responsible.<br>
<br>
Now, with 'standardized testing,' 'centralized curriculums' and 'accountable standards of learning,' we are seeing a drastic increase in the number of people slipping through the cracks.<br>
<br>
The reasons for and against this are legion and we could discuss this until the cows come home.<br>
<br>
The bottom line is this: You want good schools and smart citizens, insist that control be given back to the local municipality. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">Nakath Thunderbush<br>
