<br>
Problem is, you can't exactly lay this squarely at the feet of the concept of central standards...just the execution.<br>
<br>
1.  The textbooks we have, particularly in K-12 education, are nauseatingly PC - thanks to both liberal and conservative groups that harass textbook companies.  They're hardly factual anymore, just pathetically dull, random accounts of how people felt and thought at particular periods of history.<br>
<br>
Instead of learning about the Revolutionary War, students read pages and pages of how &quot;women influenced early America,&quot; thanks to pushes for &quot;gender equality.&quot;  And thanks to overly-patriotic conservatives, much of the early history of both World Wars is left out because &quot;the war only *really* started when the US got involved.&quot;  (Read any history book, trust me, you'll find many instances of this mealy-mouthed crap that never looks at history in a critical light, now that we talk about women and minorities in every sidebar and wouldn't *dare* look at a non-American POV in even a World History book.)<br>
<br>
2.  The standardized tests themselves suffer not only from the rampant PC bullshit, but from being, simply, confusing.  Look, I'm amazing at taking standardized tests, not to brag or anything, but it's true.  I consistently scored in the 99th percentile on all state standardized tests I took in grade school, and in the 95th percentile both on my SATs and my GREs for grad school.  I missed 1 question in the entire verbal portion of my SATs...<br>
<br>
But those tests fricking suck.  The questions are often indirect, and...verbal scores be damned, there's no words to describe how *weak* they are.  They're designed by politicians, not educators...or are at least influenced too much by legislatures.  The tests themselves need to be basic, and clear, instead of deliberately wordy and meandering.<br>
<br>
Local control is not the real answer to the education problem.  The US, I believe, has always lagged in the education department.  Most countries that have better education standards than us - the ones I'm most familliar with are Japan and Britain - have standardized tests out the wazoo.  The thing is, they COUNT.  If you fuck up that test, you are screwed.  In the US, they mean very little, and even now, mean very, very little.  When tests themselves are improved, and children MUST pass them to go on to the next grade, then, well...they learn.  It happened in the Chicago grade schools...almost all of those kids went to summer school, and many of them were able to pass the test by the end of summer.  The problem isn't the testing itself...it's the crap tests and the lack of consequences attatched to not getting it right.<br>
<br>
There's too much focus in the US on the &quot;everyone should go to college&quot; mantra.  The countries that have better educational performance than the US just laugh at that notion, and as I graduate from university myself this year, I'm beginning to see why...  So many morons with roughly 8th grade intelligence levels getting degrees.<br>
<br>
